QAbstractFactoryInterface, QAbstractInputContextFactoryInterface, QtJambiInterface
public abstract class QInputContextPlugin
extends QObject
implements QAbstractInputContextFactoryInterface, QAbstractFactoryInterface

The QInputContextPlugin class provides an abstract base for custom QInputContext plugins. The input context plugin is a simple plugin interface that makes it easy to create custom input contexts that can be loaded dynamically into applications.

To create an input context plugin you subclass this base class, reimplement the pure virtual functions keys(), create(), languages(), displayName(), and description(), and export the class with the Q_EXPORT_PLUGIN2() macro.Copyright (C) 2003-2004 immodule for Qt Project. All rights reserved.This file is written to contribute to Nokia under their own license. You may use this file under your Qt license. Following description is copied from their original file headers. Contact immodule-qt@freedesktop.org if any conditions of this licensing are not clear to you.

See also:
QInputContext, and How to Create Qt Plugins.

keys

public abstract java.util.List<java.lang.String> keys()
Returns the list of QInputContext keys this plugin provides.

These keys are usually the class names of the custom input context that are implemented in the plugin. The names are used, for example, to identify and specify input methods for the input method switching mechanism. They have to be consistent with QInputContext::identifierName(), and may only contain ASCII characters.

See also:
create(), displayName(), and QInputContext::identifierName().

Specified by:
keys in interface QAbstractFactoryInterface
Specified by:
keys in interface QAbstractInputContextFactoryInterface

languages

public abstract java.util.List<java.lang.String> languages(java.lang.String key)
Returns the languages supported by the QInputContext object specified by key.

The languages are expressed as language code (e.g. "zh_CN", "zh_TW", "zh_HK", "ja", "ko", ...). An input context that supports multiple languages can return all supported languages as QStringList. The name has to be consistent with QInputContext::language().

This information may be used to optimize user interface.

See also:
keys(), QInputContext::language(), and QLocale.

Specified by:
languages in interface QAbstractInputContextFactoryInterface
